{{infobox Shinto shrine|image=File:Toyama Chukyoin(1).png|caption=Toyama Chukyoin in the Meiji period}}

{{ill|Toyama Chukyoin|ja|富山中教院}} (富山中教院) is a shrine in [[Toyama (city)|Toyama City]].<ref name=":0">https://www.city.toyama.toyama.jp/etc/muse/tayori/tayori33/tayori33.htm</ref>{{Verify-inline|date=April 2023|reason=A japanese speaking friend helped me but she was unsure about some things}} It is quite small today. Originally its grounds were a Buddhist temple, but with the creation of the [[Taikyo Institute]] (Great Teaching Institute) a sub-institute called a Chukyoin (Medium-sized teaching institute) was created there.<ref name=":0" />{{Verify-inline|date=April 2023|reason=A japanese speaking friend helped me but she was unsure about some things}}

There were Chukyoins and Shukyoins established in each prefecture<ref name=":0" />{{Verify-inline|date=April 2023|reason=A japanese speaking friend helped me but she was unsure about some things}}<!-- I do want to put this in [[Taikyo Institute]] once it is verified -->

Around the site there was a famous night market, due to war damage it ceased to be used until it was repaired in 1950, and continues until the present day<ref name=":0" />{{Verify-inline|date=April 2023|reason=A japanese speaking friend helped me but she was unsure about some things}} 

The Chukyoin was relocated to near [[Toyama Gokoku Shrine]] in 1925 to accomodate a new streetcar line leaving only the small shrine left, the streetcar was later removed<ref name=":0" />.{{Verify-inline|date=April 2023|reason=A japanese speaking friend helped me but she was unsure about some things}} 

It is now present next to the bus stop Chukyoin Mae<ref name=":0" />{{Verify-inline|date=April 2023|reason=A japanese speaking friend helped me but she was unsure about some things}} 

It is described as the smallest shrine in Japan<ref>https://www.toyamashi-kankoukyoukai.jp/file_upload/100767/_main/100767_03.pdf</ref><!-- this japanese source also seems to support it --> 

[[File:Toyama Chukyoin.jpg|thumb|Remnants of Toyama Chukyoin today. See name on the right 富山中教院]]
